Principal Component Analysis (PCA) and Partial Least Squares (PLS)

Multicollinearity, a frequent challenge in machine learning, arises when predictor variables within a dataset exhibit strong correlations. This can lead to overfitting, where a model performs well on training data but poorly on unseen data.

Multicollinearity Test

b. Variance Inflation Factors (VIF)

The VIF values will likely be very high (probably above 10, often much higher). This confirms the multicollinearity.

# Fit a linear model (even though you might not primarily be doing linear regression,
# VIFs are still a useful diagnostic for multicollinearity among the predictors)
model <- lm(INTG ~ ., data = USJudgeRatings)  #INTG can be any variable.
vif_values <- vif(model)
print("Variance Inflation Factors (VIFs):")
## [1] "Variance Inflation Factors (VIFs):"

What to do? Given the extremely high multicollinearity, techniques like Principal Component Analysis (PCA) or Partial Least Squares (PLS) are highly recommended for this dataset. Regular linear regression would be very problematic due to the unstable coefficient estimates.

Principal Component Analysis (PCA)

Method of multivariate analysis

Principal component analysis (PCA) is a technique used to emphasize variation and bring out strong patterns in a dataset. Its often used to make data easy to explore and visualize.

If you have 20 variable,how do you understand the interrelaionship? there are 190 pairwise correlation. even though, still difficult!

It is a dimensionality reduction technique that is widely used in data analysis [visualized data is limited to 2 or 3 dimensions].

So, PCA is a data reduction technique that transforms a larger number of correlated variables into a much smaller set of uncorrelated variables called principal components

The main goals of principal component analysis is:

1.to identify hidden pattern in a data set.

2.to reduce the dimensionnality of the data by removing the noise and redundancy in the data.

3.to identify correlated variables.

Example you might use PCA to transform 30 correlated (or possibly redundant) variables into 5 uncorrelated variables (principal companants) that retains as much information from the original set.

1. Selecting the number of components to extract

We need to know how many components to be extracted, the most common approach is based on something called eigenvalues . each component is associated with eigenvalue. the 1st PC is associated with the largest eigenvalue, the 2nd PC is associated with the 2nd largest value and so on.

We will retain components with eigenvalues equal or more than 1 [role of thumb]

R can do this for you, i will use fa.parallel function in psych package

Perform parallel analysis to determine the number of components/factors

fa.parallel(USJudgeRatings, n.iter = 100, fa = "pc") # fa = "pc" for PCA
## Warning in fa.stats(r = r, f = f, phi = phi, n.obs = n.obs, np.obs = np.obs, :
## The estimated weights for the factor scores are probably incorrect.  Try a
## different factor score estimation method.

## Parallel analysis suggests that the number of factors =  NA  and the number of components =  1

as you can see in the graph this graph called Cattell Scree test, shows the eigenvalues against their component number.

horizontal lines is our criteria, eigenvalues >1 #### only 1 PC passed here, next step is to extract this PC which explains(92% of variables)

2. Extracting principal component

Using principal() function, we will extract the PC.

Perform Principal Component Analysis (PCA) - based on parallel analysis results (1 component suggested)

PCA calculates correlations of variables within the PC, called loadings or component loadings, the loadings is used to interpret the meaning of component.

By sense, loadings getting lower and lower in PC2 and PC3 (if selected).

h2 represent communalities (variance), and u2 is uniqueness.explained by the component. for example, in oral abilities of lawyers, 99% of oral varience is accounted in the pc1 and only 1% is not. It seems that oral variable is well represented in the PC1.

ssloadings is the eigenvalues associated with the component. This is the standaradized variance for the component.(here it is 10).

The proportion variance will tell you that pc1 accounts 92% of the variance in the 11 variable selected.

Cos2: checking quality of the representation for variables on the factor map

The squared loadings for variables are called cos2

The cos2 values are used to estimate the quality of the representation

The closer a variable is to the circle of correlations, the better its representation on the factor map (and the more important it is to interpret these components)

Variables that are closed to the center of the plot are less important for the first components.

pca_facto$var$cos2

Visualizing the data (using factoextra)

Now, i will show you how to plot and interpritate the PCA. This graph is called Loading plot (if you plot only the variables), or biplot sometime. I will tell you why later..

For variables

fviz_pca_var(pca_facto, col.var="coord") + scale_color_gradient2(low="white", mid="blue", high="red",midpoint=0.95) + theme_minimal()

Explanation of the PCA loading plot

what does this mean? recall the loadings pca_facto\(var\)coord.sepal length, petal length and petal width positively correlates in the PC1, thats why they are on the right side on the X axis (PC1). on the other hand, sepal width negatively contributes in the PC1, thats why its on the left side. These results are the plot of code (d).

Lets look on the PC2 (the Y axis), have a look on the loadings of the PC2. all variables affects positively on the PC2. Thans why they are on the upper half of the graph. perhaps sepal width is the most contributor.

NOTE you may need to adjust the midpoint based on your values. also , u can adjust the color based on the variables loadings (coord) or cos2.

For individuals This loads the individual contributions (code e)

fviz_pca_ind(pca_facto, col.var="cos2", pointsize=4, jitter = list(width = 0.3, height = 0.3))+scale_color_gradient2(midpoint=0.95) + theme_minimal()

Partial Least Squares (PLS)

Partial Least Squares (PLS) offers a solution. It involves standardizing predictors and the response, then creating a smaller set of uncorrelated PLS components that capture substantial variance in both. These components are then used in a linear regression. Finally, k-fold cross-validation determines the ideal number of PLS components for the model.

1. Load Necessary Packages

library(pls)
## 
## Attaching package: 'pls'
## The following object is masked from 'package:corrplot':
## 
##     corrplot
## The following object is masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     loadings

## Hornet Sportabout 18.7   8  360 175 3.15 3.440 17.02  0  0    3    2
## Valiant           18.1   6  225 105 2.76 3.460 20.22  1  0    3    1

2. Fit Partial Least Squares Model

#make this example reproducible
set.seed(1)
#fit PCR model
model <- plsr(hp~mpg+disp+drat+wt+qsec, data=mtcars, scale=TRUE, validation="CV")

scale=TRUE standardizes the predictor variables by centering them at zero mean and scaling to unit variance. This prevents variables measured on different scales from disproportionately influencing the model.

validation=CV employs k-fold (default k=10) cross-validation to assess model performance. Alternatively, validation=LOOCV performs leave-one-out cross-validation.

3. Choose the Number of PLS Components

#view summary of model fitting
summary(model)
## Data:    X dimension: 32 5 
##  Y dimension: 32 1
## Fit method: kernelpls
## Number of components considered: 5
## 
## VALIDATION: RMSEP
## Cross-validated using 10 random segments.
##        (Intercept)  1 comps  2 comps  3 comps  4 comps  5 comps
## CV           69.66    38.81    34.94    36.08    37.27    37.40
## adjCV        69.66    38.69    34.64    35.72    36.82    36.95
## 
## TRAINING: % variance explained
##     1 comps  2 comps  3 comps  4 comps  5 comps
## X     68.66    89.27    95.82    97.94   100.00
## hp    71.84    81.74    82.00    82.02    82.03

The output contains two key tables:

The first, labeled VALIDATION: RMSEP, displays the test RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error of Prediction) calculated via k-fold cross-validation.

This table reveals how the test RMSE changes with the addition of PLS components. Initially, with only the intercept, the RMSE is 69.66.

Adding the first PLS component reduces it to 38.81, and a second component further lowers it to 34.94.

However, subsequent components increase the RMSE. Therefore, a two-component model appears optimal.

The TRAINING: % variance explained table shows the percentage of response variable variance captured by the PLS components.

The first component explains 68.66% of the variance, while adding the second increases this to 89.27%.

Although additional components will always increase explained variance, the gain beyond two components is minimal.

The validationplot() function visualizes the test RMSE (along with MSE and R-squared) against the number of PLS components.

#visualize cross-validation plots
validationplot(model)

validationplot(model, val.type="MSEP")

4. Use the Final Model to Make Predictions

To predict outcomes for new data, we can apply our final two-component PLS model. The code below demonstrates how to divide the original data into training and testing sets, then uses the trained two-component PLS model to generate predictions for the held-out test data.

#define training and testing sets
train <- mtcars[1:25, c("hp", "mpg", "disp", "drat", "wt", "qsec")]
y_test <- mtcars[26:nrow(mtcars), c("hp")]
test <- mtcars[26:nrow(mtcars), c("mpg", "disp", "drat", "wt", "qsec")]
    
#use model to make predictions on a test set
model <- plsr(hp~mpg+disp+drat+wt+qsec, data=train, scale=TRUE, validation="CV")
pcr_pred <- predict(model, test, ncomp=2)

#calculate RMSE
sqrt(mean((pcr_pred - y_test)^2))
## [1] 54.89609

library(pls)
library(MASS) # For USJudgeRatings

# Load the USJudgeRatings data
data(USJudgeRatings)

# Remove the first column (presumably judge names or IDs)
judge_ratings <- USJudgeRatings[, -1]

# Make the example reproducible
set.seed(1)

# Fit PLS model (using all other variables to predict RTEN - Retention)
model <- plsr(RTEN ~ ., data = judge_ratings, scale = TRUE, validation = "CV")

# View summary of model fitting
summary(model)

# Visualize CV plots
validationplot(model)

validationplot(model, val.type = "MSEP")

# Calculate CV R-squared (as explained in previous responses)
r_squared <- function(y, y_pred) {
  1 - sum((y - y_pred)^2) / sum((y - mean(y))^2)
}

# Define training and testing sets (70/30 split)
n <- nrow(judge_ratings)
train_index <- sample(1:n, 0.7 * n)
train <- judge_ratings[train_index, ]
test <- judge_ratings[-train_index, ]
y_test <- test$RTEN  # Separate the response variable from the test set

# Refit the model on the *training* data (using the same formula)
model <- plsr(RTEN ~ ., data = train, scale = TRUE, validation = "CV")

# Use the model to make predictions on the *test* set (using optimal ncomp)
pls_pred <- predict(model, newdata = test, ncomp = 1) # Predict using optimal ncomp

# Calculate RMSE on the *test* set
rmse_test <- sqrt(mean((pls_pred - y_test)^2))
print(paste("Test RMSE:", rmse_test))
## [1] "Test RMSE: 0.248402392611099"
# Calculate R-squared on the *test* set
r_squared_test <- r_squared(y_test, pls_pred)
print(paste("Test R-squared:", r_squared_test))
## [1] "Test R-squared: 0.958194621862246"
